Based on the provided W3C documentation, I've created a PHP function to perform a registration ceremony in a WebAuthn system. This code is not meant to be a complete implementation but rather a starting point to help you understand the flow and structure of the registration process. You may need to adapt the code according to your project's requirements and additional dependencies.

Please note that there are additional dependencies required for this implementation, such as the "web-auth/webauthn-lib" library. You can install it via Composer:
```bash
composer require web-auth/webauthn-lib
```
Here's the PHP function:
```php
<?php

use Webauthn\PublicKeyCredentialCreationOptions;
use Webauthn\PublicKeyCredentialSource;
use Webauthn\PublicKeyCredentialSourceRepository;
use Webauthn\Server;
use Webauthn\TrustPath\CertificateTrustPath;

function performRegistrationCeremony(
    Server $server,
    PublicKeyCredentialCreationOptions $creationOptions,
    PublicKeyCredentialSourceRepository $credentialRepository
): void {
    // The PublicKeyCredentialCreationOptions should be configured according to the Relying Party's needs
    $publicKeyCredential = $server->createAndCheckAttestation($_POST, $creationOptions);

    $attestationObject = $publicKeyCredential->getResponse()->getAttestationObject();
    $trustPath = $attestationObject->getAttStmt()->getTrustPath();

    if ($trustPath instanceof CertificateTrustPath) {
        // Relying Party should verify the attestation trustworthiness using a trusted source or policy
        // This step depends on the Relying Party's specific implementation and trust anchors
        $trusted = isAttestationTrustworthy($trustPath);

        if (!$trusted) {
            // If attestation is not trustworthy, Relying Party should fail the registration ceremony
            throw new RuntimeException('The attestation is not trustworthy.');
        }
    }

    // Create and store a new credential record
    $publicKeyCredentialSource = PublicKeyCredentialSource::createFromPublicKeyCredential(
        $publicKeyCredential,
        $creationOptions->getUser()->getId()
    );

    // Verify the credentialId is not already registered for any user
    $existingSource = $credentialRepository->findOneByCredentialId($publicKeyCredentialSource->getPublicKeyCredentialId());

    if ($existingSource !== null) {
        // If the credentialId is already known, Relying Party should fail the registration ceremony
        throw new RuntimeException('The credentialId is already registered for a user.');
    }

    // Save the credential source in the repository
    $credentialRepository->saveCredentialSource($publicKeyCredentialSource);
}

?>
```
This function takes in a `Server`, `PublicKeyCredentialCreationOptions`, and a `PublicKeyCredentialSourceRepository`. The `Server` is responsible for creating and checking the attestation, while the `PublicKeyCredentialCreationOptions` and `PublicKeyCredentialSourceRepository` are used for setting up the registration ceremony and managing the credential storage, respectively.

You'll need to implement the `isAttestationTrustworthy` function that checks the trustworthiness of the attestation based on your application's trust anchors and policy.

